##I am overseas | spring flowers can not go out, the Greek people hold fast ah!

Micro Signal Xinminzhoukan

Function description, depth and angle —— this is what we can do.

The Greek TV bombshell calls for people to stay home, a bit like Shanghai's call to hold tight. But the liberal masses, especially the young, are not buying it. To put it bluntly, you can't go out. It's purely voluntary.

Dictation | Ms. Wu

Organize East Kim Hee

I am a post-80s Shanghainese, because the university undergraduate course is Western history, so 2006 to live in Greece so far. He is now a postdoctoral fellow in the Department of History and archaeology at the University of Athens and teaches part time Chinese at a local private educational institution.

Because Greece does not give the Chinese a special Spring Festival holiday, coupled with my classes can not leave, so I have not returned to China for many years. Usually, I keep up with the domestic news. I've been browsing since the end of last year when it was revealed that pneumonia of unknown origin had broken out at the south China Seafood Market in Wuhan.

Carnival across Europe may have accelerated the spread of the virus

Greece announced its first confirmed case of pneumonia on Feb. 26 in Thessaloniki, the largest port city in northern Greece and Greece's second largest city, in a 38 year old Greek woman who had traveled to Italy.

In February, Venice Carnival in Italy, Milan fashion week, France Munton Lemon Festival and Carnival in Nice. The events, which are largely held in southern France on the border with northern Italy, draw thousands of participants each year from all over Europe and around the world. This provided a fertile ground for the rapid spread of the new pneumonia in Europe.

Greece also has a carnival -- three weeks before it was called "pure Monday" (Kathara Deftera) . In Greece, the first full moon after the vernal equinox is the benchmark, and the first Sunday after that is the Easter of the year. Easter Monday this week is called holy Monday, and the 40th day before holy Monday is called "clear Monday" .

This year's net Monday is March 2nd, so since February 10th, Greeks have been celebrating carnival. Traditionally, the Sunday before "net Monday" is the climax and highlight of carnival. On this day, people can eat, drink and play heartily, men, women and children put on all kinds of strange clothes, carnival until late at night. Every year in every city of Greece will be held a grand carnival parade, singing and dancing.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Carnival in Greece

But in the wake of this year's outbreak, the government announced the cancellation of Carnival celebrations..

The number of confirmed cases has increased by double digits every day since March 5

When the new crown outbreak started in China, it was probably because of the good relations between China and Greece, which was reported objectively by the Greek media. Greek officials are also backing China, and Chinese Greeks have raised money to send home some of their protective gear.

The common people of Greece are also friendly to the Chinese. Greece has a population of about 11 million, and Athens, the capital, has a population of more than 4 million. Athens is a tourist city, and during the outbreak, Chinese tourists may be shunned, but this is human nature, and there is no sense of discrimination or exclusion.

After the first confirmed case was announced, supermarket traffic rose sharply the next day, with food items such as rice and Pasta most popular but not sold short. Then everyone got used to it, and although new cases were confirmed every now and then, there was no panic buying.

The inflection point was around March 5th, the day after which new cases were confirmed in the double digits every day in Greece. People are just starting to get a little nervous. By March 10, when the Greek government announced that schools would be closed for two weeks, the sense of urgency was real.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
A public school in Athens that was temporarily closed because of the outbreak

All public schools are not online because classes are suspended for only two weeks. My 8-year-old son's public elementary school, the teacher just set up a group of parents, send some links inside, let the children have time to read their own books. My 4-year-old daughter's public kindergarten has a weekly video call with her to get the lay of the land, but that's it.

Greeks greet each other when they know each other. But in this case, there's no need for such a ritual. I sometimes take a pair of sons and daughters in the vicinity of Liu Da, met their classmates and their parents, also can only far nods to greet, occasionally exchange pleasantries. Although the virus did not isolate love, but the initiative to let everyone deliberately keep at a distance, which is really mixed feelings.

The outbreak has had a limited impact on me, and my private training agency can continue to take classes online.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Ms. Wu is teaching Chinese to students online

All Leisure and entertainment venues will be closed and the purchase of disinfectants will be restricted

On March 13th the Greek government announced that shops, coffee shops and bars would be closed, but that supermarkets and pharmacies would remain open. By the next day (March 14) , the Greek TV bombshell was calling for people to stay home, a bit like Shanghai's call for a screen.

But the liberal masses, especially the young, are not buying it. After all, the Mediterranean climate of Greece, now really is the most pleasant scenery, the nest at home is a bit of a betrayal of the spring city. What's more, most of the houses in Greece are single-family houses or street-level houses. There are no such organizations as the local neighborhood committees, so they are not likely to be as tightly regulated as in China. To put it bluntly, you can't leave the house. It's all in your head.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
A shopping street in Athens

Masks are becoming harder to find in Greece because of the flu. Even if you buy a mask, like Europeans, Greeks are not used to wearing masks.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Outside a metro station on the northern outskirts of Athens, where the outbreak has reduced traffic to a trickle, few people wear masks

Disposable hand sanitizers and alcohol-based disinfectant paper that can be carried around are also tight. When I went to the drugstore, I was told I could only get two customers at a time.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
A poster of the new coronavirus is displayed in front of a pharmacy in Athens

Moreover, the purchase of disinfectant is the pharmacy's own preparation, each person can only buy two bottles.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
But there is a plentiful supply of household protective products in supermarkets. You have to clean your house thoroughly. You have everything you need.

In Athens, disposable gloves and household cleaning supplies are in plentiful supply in supermarkets

As of March 15, Greece had 228 confirmed cases across the country, which is not serious in Europe. The three deaths so far in Greece are all elderly. If ordinary people suspect they have a problem, they can apply for a new coronavirus test, and they can go to the hospital after being diagnosed, all of which are free.

In my view, the global outbreak of the new coronavirus can not be blamed on a single country, city or individual. Of course, the government does need to take some responsibility if it doesn't take it seriously enough in the first place, such as the British government being too permissive. At present, if the virus between countries unimpeded, the need for countries around the world to join together to fight the epidemic. Because viruses are the enemy of all mankind, aren't they?
